Merged Second Level Reference Label Generation Rules

Note: this merged, or common, file is intended to be used for testing a label for conflicts with existing labels irrespective of their script or language. However, it can neither be used to conclusively establish the validity of any label in the context of a specific script nor to determine whether a proposed variant label is an allocatable variant of some original label labels (for a discussion on how to use such a merged file, see Section 5.2, “Common LGR” in [RZ-LGR-Overview]).

Overview

This document specifies an integrated collection of Reference Label Generation Rules for the Second Level. While the individual Reference LGRs or LGRs based on them, may be used individually in any zone, this Common LGR is intended for resolution of label conflicts in cases where more than one of these LGRs are in use simultaneously in a given zone.

For more details on the Reference Label Generation Rules for the Second Level and their development see "Reference Label Generation Rules for the Second Level: Overview and Summary" [Level-2-Overview]. This file is intended to be used in conjunction with any combinations from the set of Second Level Reference LGR files, listed below or the LGRs derived from them; however, as noted below, certain modifications might require recomputing this Common LGR.

File Format and Conventions

The format of this file follows [RFC 7940].

By convention, any item that is common to all (or a group of) LGRs is marked with a ⍟ in the comment. This ensures that the item is recognized as not specific to a single LGR and the name for it not prefixed during integration. By convention a reflexive variant of type “out-of-repertoire-var” marks an item as not part of the current repertoire, even if it is listed in the LGR as a target for cross-repertoire variants.

For reference LGRs, a special context rule “extended-cp” is used to gate off (disable) optional members of the repertoire as described below. A special variant context rule, “enabled” is used to mark variants that are enabled as written, but may be disabled.

The use of code points of script “Common” or “Inherited” is not declared via the “language” elements in the metadata, but any admixture of ASCII code points is reflected by also declaring the language with a “Latn” script tag.

This document is a Review Draft and not final. Any version numbers shown are those of a possible future release. However, the draft may undergo significant revisions before any publication, or may be withdrawn.

Reference LGRs Merged

This file is merged from the following Second Level Reference LGRs.

  • Second Level Reference Label Generation Rules for the Arabic Script (und-Arab) [101]
  • Second Level Reference Label Generation Rules for the Armenian Script (und-Armn) [102]
  • Second Level Reference Label Generation Rules for the Bengali Script (und-Beng) [103]
  • Second Level Reference Label Generation Rules for the Chinese Language (zh-Hani) [104]
  • Second Level Reference Label Generation Rules for the Cyrillic Script (und-Cyrl) [105]
  • Second Level Reference Label Generation Rules for the Devanagari Script (und-Deva) [106]
  • Second Level Reference Label Generation Rules for the Ethiopic Script (und-Ethi) [107]
  • Second Level Reference Label Generation Rules for the Georgian Script (und-Geor) [108]
  • Second Level Reference Label Generation Rules for the Greek Script (und-Grek) [109]
  • Second Level Reference Label Generation Rules for the Gujarati Script (und-Gujr) [110]
  • Second Level Reference Label Generation Rules for the Gurmukhi Script (und-Guru) [111]
  • Second Level Reference Label Generation Rules for the Hebrew Script (und-Hebr) [112]
  • Second Level Reference Label Generation Rules for the Japanese Script (und-Jpan) [113]
  • Second Level Reference Label Generation Rules for the Kannada Script (und-Knda) [114]
  • Second Level Reference Label Generation Rules for the Khmer Script (und-Khmr) [115]
  • Second Level Reference Label Generation Rules for the Korean Script (und-Kore) [116]
  • Second Level Reference Label Generation Rules for the Lao Script (und-Laoo) [117]
  • Second Level Reference Label Generation Rules for the Latin Script (und-Latn) [118]
  • Second Level Reference Label Generation Rules for the Malayalam Script (und-Mlym) [119]
  • Second Level Reference Label Generation Rules for the Myanmar Script (und-Mymr) [120]
  • Second Level Reference Label Generation Rules for the Oriya Script (und-Orya) [121]
  • Second Level Reference Label Generation Rules for the Sinhala Script (und-Sinh) [122]
  • Second Level Reference Label Generation Rules for the Tamil Script (und-Taml) [123]
  • Second Level Reference Label Generation Rules for the Telugu Script (und-Telu) [124]
  • Second Level Reference Label Generation Rules for the Thai Language (th-Thai} [125]

Each of the Reference LGRs listed above provides the complete specification for determining both the validity of a label in the given script or language, as well as whether a proposed label is an allocatable variant for a given original label. As the set of blocked labels may contain mixed-script or cross-repertoire labels, it cannot be computed from the element LGR. The same is true for Index variants computed in collision testing. See the related description in Section 5.2 Section 5.4, "Steps in Processing a Label" in [RZ-LGR-Overview].

Merged LGR

This merged LGR has been machine generated by combining the data from all the Reference LGRs listed above plus a common preamble containing this description and the list of references used in this merged LGR. The merged LGR contains the union of the repertoire, variant mappings and Whole Label Evaluation (WLE) rules of the contributing LGRs as described in the following sections. Data that are necessarily script-dependent, such as the type for variant mappings have been removed or replaced by default values.

The XML version of this file is the normative specification, the HTML version is provided for ease of reading. That format contains additional explanatory text and other information such as summary counts or attributes looked up in the Unicode Character Database.

When processing an applied for label, this merged LGR presents the complete data and specification needed for conflict checking with any existing label, independent of script or language. This is in contrast to the individual Reference LGRs, each of which presents the complete data and specification to determine the validity of any label when applied for under that reference LGR as well as the verification of any proposed allocatable variant for the label. In particular, the merged LGR contains a complete set of all cross-script and cross-repertoire variants defined for the combined set of Element LGRs. This can be used to generate an index variant for each label: two labels with the same index variant mutually block each other, unless one is an allocatable variant of the other (which would be determined using the selected Element LGR). See also the related discussion in Section 5, "Using the LGR" in [RZ-LGR-Overview].

Repertoire

The repertoire of this merged LGR is the cumulative repertoire of all the Second Level Reference LGRs from the list above that have been integrated into this version. Those repertoires, in turn were developed based on [RZ-LGR-5] which is bounded by [MSR-5], which in turn is a subset of [Unicode 11.0]. For further details, see Section 3.2.1, “Repertoire” in [RZ-LGR-Overview].

For the second level, the repertoire has been extended beyond MSR-5 by various sets of decimal digits and the HYPHEN-MINUS (and on rare occasion by similar script-specific puncuation marks that form an integral part of words in that script).

As the repertoires are merged, any code point with a reflexive "out-of-repertoire-var" mapping in all Reference LGRs containing that code point will be considered not part of the merged repertoire and not included in the merged repertoire. This can happen if a subset of reference LGRs is merged while containing unused cross-script mappings to script not included. The merge process does not remove any code point from the individual reference LGRs.

Repertoire Listing:Each code point or range is tagged with the script or scripts with which the code point is used. Each cites the version of the Unicode Standard in which the code points were first encoded. All repertoire elements, including sequences of code points, cite each Reference LGR containing that repertoire element; see “References” below.

Optional Extensions: Repertoire elements that are considered optional extensions are given the context rule “extended-cp”. This rule is defined as matching the empty label, therefore, as written, all optional extensions are disabled. To enable an individual element, if required, remove the rule.

Some code points are also tagged with script- or language-specific classifications. These tags have been prefixed with the Unicode script identifier or language identifier in the merged LGR.

Sequences as Part of the Repertoire: Element LGRs may define sequences as members of the repertoire. In some instances these sequences may contain code point not individually listed. These code points are implicitly part of the repertoire, even though they may only appear in the context of that sequence. Sometimes sequences are defined as out-of-repertoire targets for cross-repertoire variant mappings, even though they are otherwise redundant. Such sequences may be included in the merged repertoire, or as an “imposed” variant due to cross-script variant transitivity. (Being redundant, they do not affect the set of available labels under that LGR.)

Comments

Comments provide additional information for some of the code points, but also for the definition of variants, classes, rules and actions. Where comments were merged from multiple sources, duplicates are omitted, but non-matching comments are both shown, separated by a vertical bar. A comment marked with ⍟ indicates an item explicitly shared among two or more Element LGRs, or an item required by integration.

Variants

The variant mappings in this LGR are based on the union of the non-reflexive variant mappings from all the element LGRs that have been integrated into this merged LGR. After computing the union, the variants are mechanically augmented, if needed, to ensure transitivity of the set. Any variants added during this process are identified in comments.

Variant Dispositions: Because the disposition of variant labels, for example, as “allocatable”, is specific to each script, information related to such dispositions cannot be expressed in the script- or language-neutral context of this merged file. Instead, all merged variant mappings are labeled as “blocked” in this document as needed for conflict checking. For a discussion of this approach, see Section 3.2.2, “Variants” in [RZ-LGR-Overview].

Variants of Digits: several reference LGRs for the second level contain both ASCII and native digits as semantic variants of each other, meaning digits of the same numerical value are variants. By transitivity, this makes all digits of the same value cross-script variants of each other across all reference LGRs as long as the LGR contains the ASCII digits as well. In order to keep the individual element LGRs readable, the effect of transitivity for these variants is only expressed in this merged file. This is possible because the ASCII digits are common to all affected LGRs and it is therefore possible to merge the variant relations to any script-specific digits defined in each. For almost all other cases of cross-script variants there is no such a common subset and they are therefore listed as “out-of-repertoire-var” variants in each affected element LGR.

In addition, some of the digits also are cross-script homoglyphs, meaning that they look identical. By also making them variants of the corresponding ASCII digit (whether or not the repertoire contains that ASCII digit already) we ensure that when transitivity is applied to the merged file, they become blocked variants across the scripts, without having to overburden each LGR with out-of-repertoire mappings to multiple targets.

Reflexive Variants: In the merged file, any reflexive variant mappings, including “out-of-repertoire-var” mappings have been removed from any repertoire element in the merged repertoire as these mappings do not contribute to the index variant calculation needed for collision checking. In contrast, each element LGR retains the full details of variant mappings as needed to determine variant disposition.

Suggested Variants: Some reference LGRs may have suggested variants that are enabled as written by using a context rule named “enabled”. They can be individually disabled by changing the corresponding “when” attribute to a “not-when” attribute in the XML. (Note: this convention interferes with integration, so the desired variants should have the attribute removed, and the undesired ones should be deleted, if it is desired to integrate the affected LGR.)

Implicit CRoss-script Variants: Not all element LGRs explicitly specify all variants to other scripts and repertoires, choosing instead to inherit those defined in other script LGRs implicitly. Nevertheless, as long as cross-script variants are defined in at least one LGR, they will be part of this merged LGR and are considered in effect for all LGRs that contain the relevant code points or sequences. However, in all cases, each element LGR always lists all of the applicable in-script variants.

Variant Label Processing: Only the merged LGR contains the full information needed for computing the index variant for a label needed for collision checking. The merged LGR therefore must be used to determine conflicts (two labels blocking each other) while the element LGRs are used to determine whether a given label is an allocatable variant for a particular original label under that LGR. See also Section 5, “Using the LGR” in [RZ-LGR-Overview].

Large Variant Sets: Especially for longer labels, some variant definitions may lead to variant label sets that can be very large, in some cases, so large as to not be enumerable in real time. In other cases, while the actual number variant labels is limited, the enumeration may in the worst case require the evaluation of a large number of different ways of partitioning a label into sequences.

However, given two labels, the Common LGR is designed to support very efficient determination of whether the two labels collide (block each other). Collision detection can be implemented as an O(1), or constant time algorithm that is unaffected by the number of variants defined for each. Finding out whether a label collides with any of a large number of already delegated labels can be as fast as detecting whether a particular hash code exists in a list.

The element LGRs, in turn, allow determination for a given original applied-for label whether a specific other label is an allocatable variant or not. Unlike an attempt to generate the full set of variants, this validation of variant disposition can be optimized so that it does not depend on the total number of allocatable variants.

Context Rules for Variants: some of the variants defined in this LGR are “effective null variants”, that is, some code points in the source map to “nothing” in the target with all other code points unchanged. (Because mappings are symmetric, it does not matter whether it is the forward or reverse mapping that maps to “null”). Such variants require a context rule to keep the variant set well behaved. Symmetry requires the same context rule for both forward and reverse mappings. For a discussion, see Section 6.5 in [RZ-LGR-Overview].

In other cases, the sequences or code points making up source and target are constrained by explicit context rules on the code points (or by implicit context rules defined for the adjacent code points). In such a case, any variants may require context rules that match the intersection between the effective contexts for both source and target; otherwise, a sequence might be considered valid in some variant label when it would not be valid in an equivalent context in an original label. See Section 6.4.2 in [RZ-LGR-Overview].

Overlapping Variants: Some sequences may overlap, that is, they share a common part with another sequence or code point, so that in partitioning a label into code points and sequences, more than one partition is possible. In these cases, variants have to be computed for all possible partitions. In some cases, context rules on sequences or variants are defined to curtail any unwanted side effects of such multiple partitioning, such as having each partition being part of a different variant label set, or generating a different index variant. For further discussion, see Section 6 in [RZ-LGR-Overview].

The specification of variants for the Second Level Reference LGRs follows the guidelines in [RFC 8228].

Character Classes

This merged LGR includes the cumulative set of character classes from all the element LGRs that have been integrated into this version of the merged LGR. See Section 3.2.3, “Character Classes” in [RZ-LGR-Overview]. The names for any script-specific character classes have been prefixed with the Unicode script identifier or language identifier.

Whole Label Evaluation (WLE) and Context Rules

This merged LGR includes the cumulative set of WLE and context rules and actions from all the element LGRs that have been integrated into this version of the merged LGR. For additional discussion, see Section 3.2.4, “Whole Label Evaluation Rules (WLE)" [RZ-LGR-Overview]. See also the comments given for each rule or action.

Default Whole Label Evaluation Rules and Actions

This integrated LGR includes a set of common WLE rules and actions applicable to IDNs. They are marked with ⍟. These include the restrictions defined in [RFC 5891] on placement of combining marks and HYPHEN-MINUS, as well as the default actions defined in [RFC 7940].

Note that other restrictions for IDNs, such as being lowercase, normalized to Unicode Normalization form NFC, or having an A-label of length 63 or less are not explicitly enforced by these LGRs. It is up to the application processing a label under these LGR to perform these validation steps before input, and, in the case of variant labels calculated under these LGRs, also on output.

Script- or language-specific WLE Rules

The Bidi Rule of [RFC 5893] is treated as a script- or language-specific rule for LGRs using a right-to-left script.

The names for any script-specific rules have been prefixed with the Unicode script identifier or language identifier in this file.

Script- or language-specific Actions

Some actions are triggered by script- or language-specific variant type values. While such actions are collected here for reference, they are inoperative in the context of the merged LGR because in the merged LGR all variant type values have been mapped to “blocked”, or, in the case of reflexive variants, removed.

Methodology and Contributors

The reference LGRs for the Second level were developed by Asmus Freytag and Michel Suignard following the [Guidelines]. An important input to this process are the Root Zone LGRs, and the output has been reviewed in a public process. For additional details on methodology and a full list of contributors, see Section 6 “Contributors” of [Level-2-Overview]

References [101] and above correspond to the script- or language-specific LGRs that include the repertoire item. Repertoire items may have more than one reference.
